 nowrap><b><font color='white' face='Verdana' size='2'>Gunkk</font></b></td>
        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'><font color='white' face='Verdana' size='2'> Companies changing cultures can be quite brutal against employees (and volunteers) who resist.  Customer service is a non-revenue generating function.  The Guide Program requires VI to employ people to support it... which costs more money.  VI is cutting non-revenue-generating costs to overcome the dramatic increases in expenditures they're making on EQ2, EQOA, SWG, etc... it's all just bean counting.</P><P>Mysha was right on.  Although Severine was probably 100% accurate in her assessment of the problems at SOE/VI customer service, she should have sent her complaint to the top of SOE, not to the MBs.  By going public, now she embarrasses ALL of SOE/VI, and puts them all on the defensive.  Bad move.  Instead of gaining a high-level ally, she alienated everyone.  So in the eyes of the Powers that Be at VI and by her own naive admission on the MB, she became a loose cannon.  </P><P>Loose cannons either get lashed down or thrown overboard.  </P><P>And because her own superiors were so inept at management, they couldn't keep her under control.  So they did what all inept managers do, they demote/demotivate/fire the smart employees so they don't rally the dumb ones into a mutiny.</P><P>Here's Mysha's post:<BR><BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=2 face="Verdana" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote><BR><b>Be Professional</b><BR>--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<BR> As a game developer (Unreal-Unreal Tournament) and a hardcore MMP gamer (UO-AC-DAoc-EQ) allow me to share a little advice with you.</P><P>1-Be Professional. Take your concerns and comments to those who are directly in charge of managing your guide program. Posting on message boards to vent frustrations can help you feel better, but if you truly have concerns over the success of the guide program, your efforts would be better spent taking it up with those in charge.</P><P>2-As a quasi-representative of the game and the game cmpany, your public statements directly affect the consumer's view of the company. If you are disgruntled with a volunteer program, making public negative statements is probably the worst thing you could do for yourself. Those responsible for the guide program would not be very impressed (even if your concerns are crucial and need to be addressed!)</P><P>3-If you find no way to resolve the issues you feel affect the quality of the program and are not getting the kind of action you deem necessary to improve the guide program, and still feel that major issues are just flat out wrong, then you should probably leave the program knowing that you tried to make it better and no one would listen (happens often with huge successful style companies) Better to fight to make the program better for all the great players out there internally first however. If you lose the battle and just can't take it, leave rather than making a public "rant" about it.<BR><hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana" size=2 id=quote></P><P>VI/SOE's big, they know it.  They're rich, they know it.  People will come back to playing their game even if the competition comes out with a superior product, and they know it.  They can jerk their customers around and still keep 'em, and they know it.  They know if their customers don't like it, they'll leave.</P><P>I think Mysha's right on about SOE/VI's hubris.  Either they'll snap out of it, or they'll eventually go down like all the rest.</P><P><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=310159" target="_blank">Gunkk</a><BR>47 Iksar Necro<BR>The Nameless</P><P><BR>Edited by - Gunkk on 09/17/2002  20:57:48</font></td>
